<subSubSection id="42483A1F105C8EC7AB5D4D4829DB860C" pageId="0" pageNumber="49" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="C84991A0F94CE5CFB59F936E0D94243A" pageId="0" pageNumber="49">Diagnosis.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="F566149A6F9BE2803F5BDE693592AC26" pageId="0" pageNumber="49">
<taxonomicName id="587808C63DB67FDFDE4C01F10A986F4A" authority="Dahlbom, 1854" authorityName="Rosa &amp; Halada" authorityYear="2020" class="Insecta" family="Chrysididae" genus="Spinolia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Spinolia spinosa" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="49" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="spinosa">
<emphasis id="44DADE7FCB27973F4E65C592C2DE89C0" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="49">Spinolia spinosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
sp. nov. is closely related to Central Asian species of the 
<taxonomicName id="53CA640526F837C862604D5E16B911FA" authority="Dahlbom, 1854" authorityName="Dahlbom" authorityYear="1854" baseAuthorityName="Dahlbom" baseAuthorityYear="1831" class="Insecta" family="Chrysididae" genus="Spinolia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="unicolor" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="49" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="unicolor">
<emphasis id="DD3B1290907D954D839477706D51D7FB" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="49">unicolor</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
group, which includes 
<taxonomicName id="B151931E7E1DBFCD6A82A8DAAFF8F976" genus="S." lsidName="S. chalcites" pageId="0" pageNumber="49" rank="species" species="chalcites">
<emphasis id="E4227BD3EF95411369BA9E230CC30363" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="49">S. chalcites</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<normalizedToken id="3A39239CD117EBD38A11C1BBA7618B4D" originalValue="Mocsáry">Mocsary</normalizedToken>
, 1890), 
<taxonomicName id="46EEBA152A01E1841BA64F5F0AD08C13" genus="S." lsidName="S. rusalka" pageId="0" pageNumber="49" rank="species" species="rusalka">
<emphasis id="F14C6CACC8BE97E001F4141F99152DA3" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="49">S. rusalka</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(Semenov, 1901), 
<taxonomicName id="2B21064AEAF282EF5744FC82705B39F7" genus="S." lsidName="S. hedychroides" pageId="0" pageNumber="49" rank="species" species="hedychroides">
<emphasis id="BE4A3A3BAF62EC31A8964D26508F66A6" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="49">S. hedychroides</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(Bingham, 1903) and other small species so far considered synonyms of 
<taxonomicName id="270A784E09F2306AEDEAF5ADE3ADFFC9" genus="S." lsidName="S. chalcites" pageId="0" pageNumber="49" rank="species" species="chalcites">
<emphasis id="934F6330CE6B60E719FB38CC0607B50F" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="49">S. chalcites</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(Kimsey and Bohart 1991). 
<taxonomicName id="E9BBC03FF0A5794FEDEA2D24E372BBF4" genus="S." lsidName="S. spinosa" pageId="0" pageNumber="49" rank="species" species="spinosa">
<emphasis id="7E0DFFBCD31793C4276B592AE6F5E79C" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="49">S. spinosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
sp. nov. female can be easily separated from all these species by: lateral pronotal area and propleuron ventrally V-shaped carinate, displaying two teeth in lateral view (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="9750C0217D1ABB4A7C56D890A43A6F29" captionStart="Figure 5" captionStartId="F5" captionText="Figure 5. Spinolia species, females A S. spinosa sp. nov., dorsal view B S. chalcites, dorsal view C S. unicolor, dorsal view D Spinolia spinosa sp. nov., lateral view: arrows pointing at pronotal and propleural spines. Scale bars: 1.0 mm." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.999.58536.figure5" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/481529" pageId="0" pageNumber="49">5D</figureCitation>
) (vs. unmodified in other species); mesopleuron with large and deep scrobal sulcus subtended by large projecting subrectangular carina (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="A70DBC99D4BC281815D69BF721FB86EC" captionStart="Figure 5" captionStartId="F5" captionText="Figure 5. Spinolia species, females A S. spinosa sp. nov., dorsal view B S. chalcites, dorsal view C S. unicolor, dorsal view D Spinolia spinosa sp. nov., lateral view: arrows pointing at pronotal and propleural spines. Scale bars: 1.0 mm." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.999.58536.figure5" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/481529" pageId="0" pageNumber="49">5D</figureCitation>
) (vs. U-shaped carina); sparse, deep and large punctures on mesosoma (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="810A07F4E67801677E25906E3D929A00" captionStart="Figure 6" captionStartId="F6" captionText="Figure 6. Spinolia species, females, head in frontal view (A-C), and metasoma in dorsal view (D-F). A S. spinosa sp. nov. B S. chalcites C S. unicolor. D S. spinosa sp. nov. E S. chalcites F S. unicolor. Scale bars: 1.0 mm." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.999.58536.figure6" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/481530" pageId="0" pageNumber="49">6D</figureCitation>
), and sparse and deep punctures on metasoma (vs. punctation with dense, shallow and tiny punctures on mesosoma, denser and shallower on metasoma); antennae yellowish, distinctly elongate (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="76E179ADBD12052017CEBD6774DBFE57" captionStart="Figure 5" captionStartId="F5" captionText="Figure 5. Spinolia species, females A S. spinosa sp. nov., dorsal view B S. chalcites, dorsal view C S. unicolor, dorsal view D Spinolia spinosa sp. nov., lateral view: arrows pointing at pronotal and propleural spines. Scale bars: 1.0 mm." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.999.58536.figure5" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/481529" pageId="0" pageNumber="49">5A</figureCitation>
) (vs. black to dark brown, with short to very short flagellomeres); head, in frontal view, transversely subrectangular (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="1D999C498BCF5D9B888B6036C7EA61B5" captionStart="Figure 6" captionStartId="F6" captionText="Figure 6. Spinolia species, females, head in frontal view (A-C), and metasoma in dorsal view (D-F). A S. spinosa sp. nov. B S. chalcites C S. unicolor. D S. spinosa sp. nov. E S. chalcites F S. unicolor. Scale bars: 1.0 mm." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.999.58536.figure6" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/481530" pageId="0" pageNumber="49">6A</figureCitation>
) and not triangular (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="2B7BCA09605F33830BF47CF10A47546C" captionStart="Figure 6" captionStartId="F6" captionText="Figure 6. Spinolia species, females, head in frontal view (A-C), and metasoma in dorsal view (D-F). A S. spinosa sp. nov. B S. chalcites C S. unicolor. D S. spinosa sp. nov. E S. chalcites F S. unicolor. Scale bars: 1.0 mm." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.999.58536.figure6" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/481530" pageId="0" pageNumber="49">6B</figureCitation>
); with bulging eyes, similarly to 
<taxonomicName id="FED77DFD305FE38EDAD18E693D12F2F7" genus="S." lsidName="S. unicolor" pageId="0" pageNumber="49" rank="species" species="unicolor">
<emphasis id="F6208CC8DE4712D72CD3E9658F0840AD" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="49">S. unicolor</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. It is additionally separated from 
<taxonomicName id="D6AE18749A57F4F6A6947C3065D31BC8" genus="S." lsidName="S. unicolor" pageId="0" pageNumber="49" rank="species" species="unicolor">
<emphasis id="CB8DB9B2E74D84ACBCA9A980682FB0EC" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="49">S. unicolor</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by punctation, elongate and yellowish antennae and bronze body colour (entirely blue body in 
<taxonomicName id="5622B504046BBEC3CB32B753EE2EF44C" genus="S." lsidName="S. unicolor" pageId="0" pageNumber="49" rank="species" species="unicolor">
<emphasis id="DF46AE666EE6D34CD2F7D0180FC15AC3" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="49">S. unicolor</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, with shortened, blackish flagellomeres).
</paragraph>
