<subSubSection id="EF699F1C1F0A3BAB43AD5A4EFB9923D1" pageId="0" pageNumber="49" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="4787DA1D90BF9ABCB5A7500B359E9A4C" pageId="0" pageNumber="49">Etymology.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="301446B6F03616526EA60FCCF05D7596" pageId="0" pageNumber="49">
The specific epithet 
<taxonomicName id="A60281BD77AC7695C9250CBE6603096B" genus="S." lsidName="spinosa" pageId="0" pageNumber="49" rank="species" species="spinosa">
<emphasis id="D778649A80D7144CCCE8E7F7368E5092" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="49">spinosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(feminine) is derived from the Latin adjective 
<emphasis id="83D9CC0EAFE63FD2E0FC1D03C08DE854" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="49">spinosus</emphasis>
(thorny) for the long and acute teeth ventrally displayed on pronotum and propleuron and clearly visible in lateral view (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="03545352CFD3A93575A38AD09818F5BF" captionStart="Figure 5" captionStartId="F5" captionText="Figure 5. Spinolia species, females A S. spinosa sp. nov., dorsal view B S. chalcites, dorsal view C S. unicolor, dorsal view D Spinolia spinosa sp. nov., lateral view: arrows pointing at pronotal and propleural spines. Scale bars: 1.0 mm." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.999.58536.figure5" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/481529" pageId="0" pageNumber="49">5D</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
